3
00:00:05,134 --> 00:00:07,762
Hi. This is Alessio Ferrari again.

4
00:00:07,762 --> 00:00:11,034
In the next minutes we will try,
mainly using some examples,

5
00:00:11,034 --> 00:00:14,751
to state the different approaches
that may be used in the context

6
00:00:14,751 --> 00:00:17,440
of a landslide hazard assessment.

7
00:00:17,440 --> 00:00:20,390
Let's start by trying to clarify 
what we intend

8
00:00:20,390 --> 00:00:23,022
for landslide hazard assessment.

9
00:00:23,022 --> 00:00:27,044
Hazard analysis is a fundamental component
of risk assessment.

10
00:00:27,044 --> 00:00:31,442
For a given situation, we always need 
to start with collecting data,

11
00:00:31,442 --> 00:00:34,704
in order to identify 
potential instabilities.

12
00:00:34,704 --> 00:00:37,280
Each potential instability, the danger,

13
00:00:37,280 --> 00:00:40,224
needs to be analyzed with specific tools.

14
00:00:40,224 --> 00:00:42,312
The final aim of this operation

15
00:00:42,312 --> 00:00:47,970
is to identify the susceptibility
of given areas to potential danger.

16
00:00:48,770 --> 00:00:50,685
Assessing the susceptibility

17
00:00:50,685 --> 00:00:53,527
is an operation which has
a qualitative focus,

18
00:00:53,527 --> 00:00:58,637
while hazard analysis is performed 
to provide a quantitative assessment

19
00:00:58,637 --> 00:01:01,027
of the possibility 
of a landslide to occur,

20
00:01:01,027 --> 00:01:04,959
and to identify possible hazard scenarios.

21
00:01:04,959 --> 00:01:07,339
Each potential danger 
must be characterized--

22
00:01:07,339 --> 00:01:10,189
identifying
with maximum possible precision--

23
00:01:10,189 --> 00:01:14,347
the phenomenon which may occur;
namely, the type of landslide it could be,

24
00:01:14,347 --> 00:01:18,449
initiated or activated,
what is the extension of the phenomena,

25
00:01:18,449 --> 00:01:22,479
and the area that can be 
potentially affected by it.

26
00:01:22,479 --> 00:01:27,330
The intensity will provide an indication
on the severity of the phenomena.

27
00:01:27,330 --> 00:01:30,993
All these mentioned elements,
which are part of the landslide analysis,

28
00:01:30,993 --> 00:01:35,068
are fundamental ingredients
in order to assess the consequences

29
00:01:35,068 --> 00:01:37,093
related to the phenomena.

30
00:01:37,093 --> 00:01:39,912
In particulary, the study of 
the type of danger

31
00:01:39,912 --> 00:01:42,463
and the areas that are affected
by the landslide,

32
00:01:42,463 --> 00:01:46,421
will serve to identify 
the elements which are at risk.

33
00:01:46,421 --> 00:01:49,763
At the same time, the intensity 
will serve as an ingredient

34
00:01:49,763 --> 00:01:52,209
together with the vulnerability 
of the elements,

35
00:01:52,209 --> 00:01:54,512
to quantify the consequences.

36
00:01:54,512 --> 00:01:57,437
Even for the case of 
a simple rock block falling,

37
00:01:57,437 --> 00:02:01,674
the quantification of those ingredients
may require dedicated analysis.

38
00:02:01,674 --> 00:02:04,165
In this particular case, 
we would need to know

39
00:02:04,165 --> 00:02:07,866
the mass and positioning 
of the block that is likely to fall;

40
00:02:07,866 --> 00:02:10,246
the area that can be 
affected by the fall

41
00:02:10,246 --> 00:02:13,218
that will depend mainly 
on the trajectory of the block;

42
00:02:13,218 --> 00:02:17,356
and so the elements 
that could be impacted can be identified.

43
00:02:18,054 --> 00:02:21,445
The speed of the block could serve
as an indicator for the intensity,

44
00:02:21,445 --> 00:02:24,686
which would let us computing
the potential damages done

45
00:02:24,686 --> 00:02:28,258
to the infrastructures or buildings
impacted by the block.

46
00:02:28,838 --> 00:02:31,100
Also the definition 
of occurrence probability

47
00:02:31,100 --> 00:02:33,310
is part of the hazard analysis,

48
00:02:33,310 --> 00:02:36,506
together with the quantification 
of the consequences,

49
00:02:36,506 --> 00:02:39,617
is the key ingredient to compute the risk.

50
00:02:40,317 --> 00:02:43,267
The example of the block 
that we've just discussed,

51
00:02:43,267 --> 00:02:47,760
is already anticipating how complex
hazard analysis for a landslide can be.

52
00:02:48,350 --> 00:02:52,500
Scientists and stakeholders 
often try to overcome this complexity

53
00:02:52,500 --> 00:02:54,990
by using simple approaches.

54
00:02:54,990 --> 00:02:57,339
Here, we see the example 
of a hazard analysis

55
00:02:57,339 --> 00:03:00,182
for rainfall induced landslides.

56
00:03:00,182 --> 00:03:02,772
By collecting information on past events

57
00:03:02,772 --> 00:03:05,860
here, in terms of rainfall
intensity and duration

58
00:03:05,860 --> 00:03:08,415
from which a landslide has been produced

59
00:03:08,415 --> 00:03:13,754
it appears reasonable to draw thresholds,
